vitejs/vite#20611.body:
### Documentation is

- [ ] Missing
- [ ] Outdated
- [x] Confusing
- [ ] Not sure?

### Explain in Detail

There seems to be contradictory language regarding whether or not Vite loads environment variables from `.env` files. On the ["Configuring Vite"](https://vite.dev/config/#using-environment-variables-in-config) page it states:

> Note that Vite doesn't load `.env` files by default as the files to load can only be determined after evaluating the Vite config, for example, the `root` and `envDir` options affect the loading behaviour. However, you can use the exported `loadEnv` helper to load the specific .env file if needed.

However on the ["Env Variables and Modes"](https://vite.dev/guide/env-and-mode.html#env-files) page it states:

> Vite uses `dotenv` to load additional environment variables from the following files in your environment directory ... Vite will always load `.env` and `.env.local` in addition to the mode-specific `.env.[mode]` file.

 It's seems unclear what the default behaviour is because of this, does Vite load `.env` by default or not? The simple answer is that the "Env Variables and Modes" documentation is correct, and Vite does load `.env` files and makes (correctly prefixed) variables available to the app by default.

I think the source of the confusion is that "Configuring Vite" is referring to whether or not environment variables from `.env` are available _within the config file itself_. Vite _does_ load the `.env`, but after the config has been processed not during. So `.env` variables are available to the app via `import.meta.env` but not available to the config via `process.env` unless you use `loadEnv`. This is maybe supposed to be clear from the context of the page, but I don't think the average reader looking for an explanation of `.env` in Vite would understand that at first glance and the language itself doesn't contain any of that important context.

### Your Suggestion for Changes

I think ["Env Variables and Modes"](https://vite.dev/guide/env-and-mode.html#env-files) is essentially correct and can be left as is, but ["Configuring Vite"](https://vite.dev/config/#using-environment-variables-in-config) should be updated to clarify the distinction. It should say something along the lines of:

---

Environmental variables for configuration purposes within your Vite config file can be obtained from `process.env` (as usual in node applications).

Note however that Vite doesn't load `.env` files by default while processing the config, as the files to load can only be determined after evaluating the Vite config. For example, the `root` and `envDir` options affect the loading behaviour. If you need to access environment variables from `.env` in your configuration file you can use the exported `loadEnv` helper to load the specific `.env` file.

> [!NOTE]
> Environment variables in `.env` files will be made available to the _application_ via `import.meta.env` by default. If you are simply trying to pass along variables from a `.env` file to your app, `loadEnv` is not required. See [this documentation for more on how environment variables and modes](https://vite.dev/guide/env-and-mode.html#env-variables-and-modes) work in Vite.

```javascript
import { defineConfig, loadEnv } from 'vite'

export default defineConfig(({ mode }) => {
  // Load env file based on `mode` in the current working directory.
  // Set the third parameter to '' to load all env regardless of the
  // `VITE_` prefix.
  const env = loadEnv(mode, process.cwd(), '')
  return {
    // vite config
    define: {
      __APP_ENV__: JSON.stringify(env.APP_ENV), // the loaded env variables can be used to define env var overrides
    },
    server: {
      port: env.APP_PORT ?? '5173', // or they can be used for anything else you need, like conditional options overrides.
    },
  }
})
```

---

I will try to make a PR with this change suggestion If I get a minute.

